Arun and Chavan (2009) reported problems involving frequent arguments with parents,
criticizing and interfering attitudes of parents, disagreements between students and their parents,
and poor trust, high expectations, and a lack of guidance by parents. In many families, parents
disregard their children's abilities and capacities and impose various expectations (Bhargava &
Tiwari, 2019). The high competition among peers in school often causes parents to criticize their
children and compare their performance with the best in class (Deb et al., 2015). Parents express
embarrassment, disappointment, and "hate" for students due to poor academic performances
(Parikh et al., 2019). Increasing unemployment, personal experiences, and a desire for the best
opportunities for their children has made parents authoritative in their children's life choices
concerning education, career, partner, etc. (Parikh et al., 2019). This highly competitive academic
environment has led to the strict supervision of students, with parents reportedly removing
television connections, cutting down on their own social lives, and appointing numerous private
tutors to help students improve academically, boost participation in extra-curricular activities,
and help in the completion of homework (Deb et al., 2015; Verma et al. 2002). Furthermore,
studies suggest additional parental pressure on girls due to prevalent sexism and parental
expectations to follow traditional gender roles such as household chores (Parikh et al., 2019).
All these factors vastly reduce recreational time and promote extreme anxiety-related
issues and fear of schools and parents. Instead of assuming a supportive role, parents themselves
undertake a pressurizing stance on students, adding to the academic stress (Deb et al., 2015).
